commentBody:
@Steve L 

Your calling out "I notice how you didn’t write the whole definition" seems to imply I was trying to pull the wool over everyone's eyes, when in fact, I was just lazy, and figured the educated audience could fill in the rest.  

For the record, one full definition is:  "a long and eventful or adventurous journey or experience."  I think you're splitting hairs saying "Odyssey" is not a long work, when the work is based on a "long and eventful or adventurous journey or experience".  Or so I gathered about the work, as I've not read it.  I did love "O Brother Where Art Thou".

@Asher A guitar is kind of ax-shaped, if you think of the neck as the handle. 

The chatacter Marceline in the Adult Swim series "Adventure Time" plays an electric base made from her dad's battle ax, with the handle as the neck.

I've been learning classical guitar for the past two years. My teacher, who is a very respected professional musician, will occasionally refer to a guitar as an "ax."

@G

I grew up with them (late 70’s, early 80’s) because my mother the french fry connoisseur preferred them to frozen fries. Very popular on "Dad's out of town and I don't feel like cooking" night.

Now I want a Manwich and tots.

@G 

Rod Stewart was the first rod that came to mind for me as well. 

(Always nice to read a comment of yours.) :-)

@G 

Per Wikipedia, Rod Stewart had a separate solo contract when he was with Faces and Maggie May is on one of his solo albums.

Thanks for sparking my desire to look that up, because I remembered the album cover clearly with the name "Rod Stewart" emblazoned on it.

@sotto voce @G et al

This is arguably Rod and car related. The album version had some nice instrumentals, but this is pure early seventies Stewart.  Compare this to the digitized, autotuned recorded vocals we get today.

<a href="https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=HLBFyS2hlhw" target="_blank">https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=HLBFyS2hlhw</a>

@Steve 

I should have thought to check the interwebs before posting - instead I asked my partner, even down to whether Faces is prefaced by "The". Lol! 

I had always thought Maggie May was Rod solo, but years ago was disabused of that notion by my partner... Neither of us owned the album, and I don't ever recall seeing it in the record store bins!

@Warren 

Thanks for that. What a voice! Raw power, and in open air no less - no carefully controlled recording studio here. 

The person hanging out their window at the end is a nice touch - the vocals are so clear I almost thought it could have been on a theater set!

@Carl 

Well.....don't let us stop you...but I must say there are just so many worse things to get all bent out of shape about....
Such as a clue that claims COD is typical for fish-and-chips, when plaice is more traditional (and less-threatened as a species.)

@Matt Kopans It’s one of those times when the editors didn’t bother with accuracy and so you have to put in something that doesn’t make sense.

The oboe as you note is a woodwind, not a brass instrument. If it’s cousins with a horn, it must be cousins with literally anything used to make music. 

IOW: this was bad clue that should not have survived to print.

@Chet 

As Matt Kopan noted, he misread the clue, which says [Smaller cousins of English horns], which is in fact true.

In other words, this was a perfectly fine clue.

@Chet 

What's going on with you?

Did an editor insult you or something, that brought on this level of disdain?

@Linda Jo 
I certainly agree...as "rods" go, that would be mighty flimsy.  And it's a rare car, these days, that has a visible antenna of that sort.  
Some days I wonder if Joel & Co. are really Old People disguised as young hipsters....

@David Connell,

Thank you for this. So much interesting information here. Others might mistake it for trivia. 

(“From the Latin word *trivium*, which means "crossroads" or "a place where three roads meet")

@Barry Ancona 

Hmmm.

Examples?

@Mr Dave 

I'd be interested in seeing some also.


...

@Rosalind Mitchell 
Haha! For all you Yanks who didn't have a Scottish girlfriend, "pants" means underpants, and is slang for rubbish. I think it's either "trews" or "breeks" for what we call pants, but one of those might be archaic.

I'm currently picturing Mike Myers, dressed as an older gent in a kilt, singing "D'ya Think I'm Sexy" with a bagpiper.

@Rosalind Mitchell 
Less of the London chippies young lady; it’s cod all the way for me and I’m a Northerner by birth. Haddock is too dry to soak up the batter properly.

Lolled at @David @Grant having to explain pants. Well done chaps!

@Grant 

Trousers will do. Think of the Oscar-winning Wallace & Gromit short, The Wrong Trousers. If you haven't seen it, give yourself a treat and see it out.

Trews and especially breeks are heard in Scotland. Both are from the Gàidhlig: triubhas in the first instance and briogais in the second. Trews are the tartan pants you might wear to play golf.

@Rosalind Mitchell 

To your point, I always understood fish & chips traditionally to be made from haddock, not cod. 

These days, with the price of cod (and really, basically all fish) going up, local spots often use other white fish, such as hake...
